00:10:57,206 --> 00:11:01,167
And these are the weapons that have unique movie sound reference.

139
00:11:01,167 --> 00:11:06,809
And what I mean by unique here is the character of the weapon never changes throughout the

140
00:11:06,809 --> 00:11:12,251
movies and they don't reuse the sound that previously appeared for something else.

141
00:11:13,114 --> 00:11:23,318
Reusing sounds like that is never a problem in the movies because there's often a lot of time that passes in between those moments and what matters more there is what works for that scene.

142
00:11:23,318 --> 00:11:35,163
But in the game you can have all weapons potentially next to each other and it wouldn't be good for player information to have some of them share the same assets.

143
00:11:35,163 --> 00:11:40,025
And also when you unlock a new weapon you don't really want it to sound like what you just had before.

144
00:11:43,040 --> 00:11:46,723
So how did we approach making most sounds in the game?

145
00:11:46,723 --> 00:11:50,225
First off, we would define what the sound is.

146
00:11:50,225 --> 00:11:51,486
We would look at the reference.

147
00:11:51,486 --> 00:11:53,508
We would see how clear is the reference,

148
00:11:53,508 --> 00:11:55,769
and does it overlap with anything.

149
00:11:55,769 --> 00:11:59,452
Often, if there is a reference, then we

150
00:11:59,452 --> 00:12:01,113
would remaster the assets.

151
00:12:01,113 --> 00:12:04,536
Here's a spectrogram example of a Tatooine wind.

152
00:12:04,536 --> 00:12:07,458
So you read it bottom to top, low frequencies

153
00:12:07,458 --> 00:12:08,479
to high frequencies.

154
00:12:08,479 --> 00:12:11,601
And as you can hopefully see on the right side.

155
00:12:12,485 --> 00:12:15,106
There's more content in the higher frequency ranges, which

156
00:12:15,106 --> 00:12:20,487
is what you lose mostly through older recordings on tape.

157
00:12:20,487 --> 00:12:24,889
And we do that through a variety of tools

158
00:12:24,889 --> 00:12:30,471
where we bring out some of the weaker or filtered frequencies.

159
00:12:30,471 --> 00:12:32,772
And we would also add content on top that

160
00:12:32,772 --> 00:12:34,652
fits to the source underneath.

161
00:12:38,708 --> 00:12:40,570
When we make something new, of course,

162
00:12:40,570 --> 00:12:42,691
we have to make sure that it seamlessly

163
00:12:42,691 --> 00:12:44,413
fits into the soundscape.

164
00:12:44,413 --> 00:12:47,015
Ideally, someone new to Star Wars,

165
00:12:47,015 --> 00:12:49,597
maybe someone like that exists, would not

166
00:12:49,597 --> 00:12:53,700
be able to tell the difference between an old Star Wars

167
00:12:53,700 --> 00:12:55,421
sound and a new one.

168
00:12:55,421 --> 00:12:57,102
So speaking of fitting in, you don't

169
00:12:57,102 --> 00:13:04,808
want to end up with this, where clearly this person is

170
00:13:04,808 --> 00:13:05,628
Photoshopped in.

171
00:13:09,910 --> 00:13:12,231
So when we have the content, we would then

172
00:13:12,231 --> 00:13:17,013
build a modular system for the runtime behavior.

173
00:13:17,013 --> 00:13:19,955
And that helps us to make the experience very

174
00:13:19,955 --> 00:13:25,637
immersive through a high amount of variation

175
00:13:25,637 --> 00:13:27,298
and being very adaptable to the game's conditions.

176
00:13:27,298 --> 00:13:32,500
So I'm going to go through an example with the classic E11

177
00:13:32,500 --> 00:13:37,422
blaster that everyone knows.

178
00:13:37,422 --> 00:13:38,203
And this is the.

179
00:13:39,259 --> 00:13:40,840
This is the visual scripting.

180
00:13:40,840 --> 00:13:44,922
This is a sound graph for the firing logic.

181
00:13:44,922 --> 00:13:49,824
So here on the left, we see in these red boxes,

182
00:13:49,824 --> 00:13:51,524
it's six layers.

183
00:13:51,524 --> 00:13:54,506
Each layer represents a sound in itself.

184
00:13:54,506 --> 00:13:58,968
And it can be something like the bass punch, the core laser,

185
00:13:58,968 --> 00:14:02,169
and the short-term reflections and long-term reflections.

186
00:14:03,380 --> 00:14:11,162
And some of those layers have sub-layers where the content changes based on environment and

187
00:14:11,162 --> 00:14:13,002
distance to the listener.

188
00:14:13,002 --> 00:14:17,423
And each of those sounds has a number of variations.

189
00:14:17,423 --> 00:14:23,545
So if you add everything up you end up with roughly 150 unique sound files used for the

190
00:14:23,545 --> 00:14:24,585
E11 blaster firing.

191
00:14:25,307 --> 00:14:30,490
And 20% of those roughly are based on the movie reference

192
00:14:30,490 --> 00:14:35,013
and based in terms of modified to fit the gameplay

193
00:14:35,013 --> 00:14:35,653
perspectives.

194
00:14:35,653 --> 00:14:36,454
And then if you do the math, you end up

195
00:14:36,454 --> 00:14:40,296
with roughly 700,000 variations for firing

196
00:14:40,296 --> 00:14:41,717
the weapon in first person.

197
00:14:41,717 --> 00:14:44,079
And that sounds maybe excessive, but.

198
00:14:49,465 --> 00:14:52,386
In practice, some layers stand out more than others.

199
00:14:52,386 --> 00:14:54,287
And we realized that very early on,

200
00:14:54,287 --> 00:14:56,428
especially when there was just one blaster

201
00:14:56,428 --> 00:14:58,709
and everyone fired it.

202
00:14:58,709 --> 00:15:02,750
You would run into synthetic sounding repetition very fast.

203
00:15:02,750 --> 00:15:05,091
And we want to avoid that at all costs

204
00:15:05,091 --> 00:15:07,672
because we don't want the player to think about the game

205
00:15:07,672 --> 00:15:13,714
as sound files being played from a hard drive or memory.

206
00:15:13,714 --> 00:15:17,936
We want the player to think the sound exists in the world.

207
00:15:19,253 --> 00:15:26,960
So we add a lot of parameter randomization where we modulate individual layer amplitude,

208
00:15:26,960 --> 00:15:28,962
pitch, and timing offsets.

209
00:15:28,962 --> 00:15:34,467
And that basically keeps the weapon constantly evolving and changing

210
00:15:34,467 --> 00:15:38,931
and it keeps it alive and organic.

211
00:15:38,931 --> 00:15:40,172
We do some filtering, so...

212
00:15:41,035 --> 00:15:43,777
Even though we change content on distance,

213
00:15:43,777 --> 00:15:46,798
we also help it out more with filtering,

214
00:15:46,798 --> 00:15:49,900
where we cut low end and high shelf.

215
00:15:49,900 --> 00:15:53,902
We also filter based on perspective and angle.

216
00:15:53,902 --> 00:15:56,643
So perspective being first person, third person,

217
00:15:56,643 --> 00:16:00,125
shooting from the hip, shooting when scoped.

218
00:16:00,125 --> 00:16:02,506
And angle, well, if it's shooting towards you

219
00:16:02,506 --> 00:16:04,167
or away from you.

220
00:16:04,167 --> 00:16:06,328
And it's most dangerous, most sharp

221
00:16:06,328 --> 00:16:07,449
when it's shooting towards you.

222
00:16:10,247 --> 00:16:15,108
We do some further randomization through peaking filters,

223
00:16:15,108 --> 00:16:19,329
where we randomly dip or boost certain frequencies

224
00:16:19,329 --> 00:16:21,289
within a defined range.

225
00:16:21,289 --> 00:16:24,410
And that basically makes every instance of their weapon

226
00:16:24,410 --> 00:16:28,731
that exists on the map always unique in the sense

227
00:16:28,731 --> 00:16:32,612
that it is a subtle, but if you have 10 players

228
00:16:32,612 --> 00:16:34,753
shooting the same weapon at the same distance

229
00:16:34,753 --> 00:16:37,233
in the same environment, still each E11

230
00:16:37,233 --> 00:16:39,654
will have a slight unique touch to it.

