00:29:08,074 --> 00:29:09,495
believing it's diatonic music,

374
00:29:09,495 --> 00:29:11,698
even though it becomes chromatic.

375
00:29:13,918 --> 00:29:18,440
Fast moving woodwind runs to bridge transitions or to add excitement.

376
00:29:18,440 --> 00:29:27,125
Woodwinds doubling brass in an octave above to kind of add a shimmer or a brightness to the sound

377
00:29:27,125 --> 00:29:31,167
is a very typical John Williams orchestration trick.

378
00:29:31,167 --> 00:29:39,751
Fast moving tremolo lines and strings that sort of add momentum to build into new sections

379
00:29:39,751 --> 00:29:42,573
or add some excitement or some anticipation, if you will.

380
00:29:43,655 --> 00:29:47,656
And then counterpoint, this is something that John Williams,

381
00:29:47,656 --> 00:29:49,176
in my opinion, is a master at.

382
00:29:49,176 --> 00:29:53,758
And if I studied anything more than anything else,

383
00:29:53,758 --> 00:29:55,398
it was his use of counterpoint

384
00:29:55,398 --> 00:29:59,219
and then started to internalize that for myself.

